<p><b>What happened to Elizabeth Bishop?</b> In 1971, She read from her works at Vassar during the AAAVC Centennial Celebration and, at 68, she returned on May 2, 1979 “for an encore performance.” In October of that year, Bishop died, of a brain aneurism, in Boston, Massachusetts.</p>
<p><b>What is Elizabeth Bishop most famous for?</b> She received the 1956 Pulitzer Prize for her collection Poems: North & South/A Cold Spring (Houghton Mifflin, 1955). Her Complete Poems (Farrar, Straus and Giroux, 1969), won the National Book Award in 1970. That same year, Bishop began teaching at Harvard University, where she worked for seven years.</p>
<p><b>Is Elizabeth Bishop a good poet?</b> Elizabeth Bishop is one of the greatest poets of the 20th century. When she died in 1979, she had only published four collections, yet had won virtually every major American literary award, including the Pulitzer Prize.</p>
