<p><b>What language is "thou art"?</b> These words — “art,” “thou,” “thee,” “thy,” and “doth” are all archaic (old and for the most part outdated), and are part of Early Modern English, which was spoken during the transition from Middle English (spoken during the Middle Ages/medieval time period) and Modern English, which we speak now.</p>
<p><b>Does thou mean God?</b> Modern Quakers who choose to use this manner of "plain speaking" often use the "thee" form without any corresponding change in verb form, for example, is thee or was thee. In Latter-day Saint prayer tradition, the terms "thee" and "thou" are always and exclusively used to address God, as a mark of respect.</p>
